      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems from ASME V&V 10 suite solved with known analytical solutions; maximum allowable error 1% for linear elastic benchmarks. Gradation 2 requires at least one relevant benchmark demonstrating solver correctness.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using ASME V&V 10 benchmark problems including a cantilever beam under end load and a thick-walled cylinder under internal pressure. Computed results matched analytical solutions within 0.3%, confirming Gradation 2 code verification."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study required; discretization error estimated via Richardson extrapolation; GCI < 5% for all reported QoIs. Gradation 3 requires formal convergence study with error quantification.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was conducted using three mesh densities (coarse: ~85k elements, medium: ~210k elements, fine: ~520k elements). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.8%, 2.4%, and 1.2% for stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm respectively, all below the 5% threshold. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver convergence criteria documented; force and displacement residuals < 1e-4 for all load steps. Gradation 2 requires documented convergence monitoring.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson iterative solver convergence was monitored across all load steps. Force residuals converged to below 1e-5 and displacement residuals to below 1e-4 for all 11 simulated constructs. Gradation 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup reviewed by a second qualified analyst; checklist-based review documented. Gradation 2 requires independent review of boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions.",
      "rationale": "An independent qualified analyst reviewed all model inputs, boundary conditions, contact definitions, and material property assignments prior to execution. A structured checklist was completed and archived. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified with literature references; nonlinear material behavior captured for titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) using bilinear isotropic hardening. Gradation 3 requires physics justification and sensitivity analysis of model form assumptions.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening was selected for Ti-6Al-4V based on published stress-strain data. A model form sensitivity analysis compared linear elastic, bilinear isotropic, and multilinear kinematic hardening formulations; differences in QoIs were less than 3% between bilinear and multilinear models, confirming that the chosen form is adequate. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from coupon testing of the same material lot; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of test articles; input uncertainty quantified and propagated. Gradation 3 requires traceable inputs with uncertainty characterization.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus (114 GPa ± 3 GPa) and yield strength (880 MPa ± 15 MPa) were measured from coupon specimens machined from the same material lot as the test constructs. UHMWPE block properties were taken from ISO 5834-2 characterization data. Geometric dimensions were confirmed by CMM measurements. Input uncertainty was propagated via Latin hypercube sampling (n=200 runs). Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N ≥ 10 test constructs assembled from production-representative components; sample traceability to device design history file confirmed. Gradation 3 requires statistically adequate sample size with traceability.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production-representative components with full traceability to the device design history file. Samples were distributed across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6, Lab 2: n=5) to assess inter-laboratory variability. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple loading rates and environmental conditions tested to bracket COU operating range; at minimum two distinct test configurations. Gradation 3 requires multi-condition testing; Gradation 2 accepted here with documented risk acknowledgment.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single ASTM F1717 static compression-bending condition (displacement-controlled, 1 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature). While the COU encompasses quasi-static loading only, the restriction to a single test condition limits the ability to characterize loading-rate sensitivity. Gradation 2 is achieved rather than the required Gradation 3. This shortfall is acknowledged in the overall credibility assessment; the model risk level of 3 and medium model influence together mean that the single-condition limitation does not preclude an overall Accepted determination, consistent with the V&V 40 framework's allowance for compensating factors across the factor portfolio."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs matched to experimental conditions within documented tolerances; any discrepancies between nominal and as-tested values explicitly accounted for in model inputs. Gradation 3 requires full traceability between experimental and simulation input parameters.",
      "rationale": "All simulation input parameters were matched to experimentally measured values: screw geometry from CMM, UHMWPE block dimensions from caliper measurement, applied displacement profile from test machine data acquisition. Discrepancies between nominal and as-measured dimensions were less than 0.05 mm for all critical features. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Predicted QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) were compared to experimental results using two metrics: (1) percent difference between mean predicted and mean experimental values, and (2) the validation metric E/uval per ASME V&V 20. For all three QoIs, percent differences were below 10% (stiffness: 4.2%, yield force: 6.8%, force at 40 mm: 3.1%) and E/uval ratios were below 1.96 (stiffness: 1.41, yield force: 1.73, force at 40 mm: 1.18). The output comparison methodology, threshold derivation, and statistical treatment are fully described in the validation report (Nagaraja et al., 2018). The required Gradation 3 demands that comparison be performed using a formally defined metric that accounts for both model prediction uncertainty and experimental measurement uncertainty, with a pre-specified threshold that reflects the clinical decision context. The threshold of E/uval < 1.96 corresponds to a 95% confidence interval interpretation under the assumption of normally distributed errors, which is appropriate for the medium-consequence COU where prediction errors leading to under-designed constructs could result in revision surgery. The stiffness QoI carries the greatest clinical weight because it governs load transfer to the adjacent vertebral segment; yield force governs the onset of permanent deformation; and force at 40 mm governs the ultimate load-bearing capacity in worst-case bending scenarios. All three QoIs individually satisfy the acceptance threshold, providing multi-dimensional validation evidence. Inter-laboratory variability between Lab 1 and Lab 2 was assessed and found to be within normal experimental scatter (CV < 8% across all QoIs), confirming that the combined dataset is suitable for validation. Gradation 3 is achieved for this factor."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes; traceability from QoI to device risk analysis documented. Gradation 3 requires explicit mapping of QoIs to COU decision needs.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly linked to the clinical failure modes identified in the device FMEA: fatigue crack initiation (yield force), loss of fixation (stiffness), and catastrophic fracture (force at 40 mm). Traceability from QoI to risk analysis is documented. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions; any gaps between validation scenario and COU explicitly characterized. Gradation 3 requires high fidelity match between validation activity and COU.",
      "rationale": "The ASTM F1717 bench test configuration directly replicates the loading and boundary conditions of the COU: same screw design, same UHMWPE block geometry, same compression-bending load application. The validation scenario is essentially identical to the COU scenario, providing high relevance. Gradation 3 achieved."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels. The single shortfall (Test conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is acknowledged and documented. Given the medium model influence, medium decision consequence, and the multi-QoI validation evidence demonstrating FEA predictions within pre-established acceptance bounds across two independent laboratories, the overall credibility of the FEA model for the stated COU is judged sufficient to support the regulatory submission. The overall assessment is Accepted.",
